17565
17586 void push_back(basic_json&& val)
17587 {
17588 // push_back only works for null objects or arrays
17589 if (JSON_UNLIKELY(not(is_null() or is_array())))
17590 {
17591 JSON_THROW(type_error::create(308, "cannot use push_back() with " + std::string(type_name())));
17592 }
17593
17594 // transform null object into an array
17595 if (is_null())
17596 {
17597 m_type = value_t::array;
17598 m_value = value_t::array;
17599 assert_invariant();
17600 }
17601
17602 // add element to array (move semantics)
17603 m_value.array->push_back(std::move(val));
17604 // invalidate object: mark it null so we do not call the destructor
17605 // cppcheck-suppress accessMoved
17606 val.m_type = value_t::null;
17607 }
17608
17613 reference operator+=(basic_json&& val)
17614 {
17615 push_back(std::move(val));
17616 return *this;
17617 }
17618
17623 void push_back(const basic_json& val)
17624 {
17625 // push_back only works for null objects or arrays
17626 if (JSON_UNLIKELY(not(is_null() or is_array())))
17627 {
17628 JSON_THROW(type_error::create(308, "cannot use push_back() with " + std::string(type_name())));
17629 }
17630
17631 // transform null object into an array
17632 if (is_null())
17633 {
17634 m_type = value_t::array;
17635 m_value = value_t::array;
17636 assert_invariant();
17637 }
17638
17639 // add element to array
17640 m_value.array->push_back(val);
17641 }
17642
17647 reference operator+=(const basic_json& val)
17648 {
17649 push_back(val);
17650 return *this;
17651 }
17652
17673 void push_back(const typename object_t::value_type& val)
17674 {
17675 // push_back only works for null objects or objects
17676 if (JSON_UNLIKELY(not(is_null() or is_object())))
17677 {
17678 JSON_THROW(type_error::create(308, "cannot use push_back() with " + std::string(type_name())));
17679 }
17680
17681 // transform null object into an object
17682 if (is_null())
17683 {
17684 m_type = value_t::object;
17685 m_value = value_t::object;
17686 assert_invariant();
17687 }
17688
17689 // add element to array
17690 m_value.object->insert(val);
17691 }
17692
17697 reference operator+=(const typename object_t::value_type& val)
17698 {
17699 push_back(val);
17700 return *this;
17701 }
17702
17728 void push_back(initializer_list_t init)
17729 {
17730 if (is_object() and init.size() == 2 and (*init.begin())->is_string())
17731 {
17732 basic_json&& key = init.begin()->moved_or_copied();
17733 push_back(typename object_t::value_type(
17734 std::move(key.get_ref<string_t&>()), (init.begin() + 1)->moved_or_copied()));
17735 }
17736 else
17737 {
17738 push_back(basic_json(init));
17739 }
17740 }
17741
17746 reference operator+=(initializer_list_t init)
17747 {
17748 push_back(init);
17749 return *this;
17750 }
17751
17773 template<class... Args>
17774 void emplace_back(Args&& ... args)
17775 {
17776 // emplace_back only works for null objects or arrays
17777 if (JSON_UNLIKELY(not(is_null() or is_array())))
17778 {
17779 JSON_THROW(type_error::create(311, "cannot use emplace_back() with " + std::string(type_name())));
17780 }
17781
17782 // transform null object into an array
17783 if (is_null())
17784 {
17785 m_type = value_t::array;
17786 m_value = value_t::array;
17787 assert_invariant();
17788 }
17789
17790 // add element to array (perfect forwarding)
17791 m_value.array->emplace_back(std::forward<Args>(args)...);
17792 }
17793
17821 template<class... Args>
17822 std::pair<iterator, bool> emplace(Args&& ... args)
17823 {
17824 // emplace only works for null objects or arrays
17825 if (JSON_UNLIKELY(not(is_null() or is_object())))
17826 {
17827 JSON_THROW(type_error::create(311, "cannot use emplace() with " + std::string(type_name())));
17828 }
17829
17830 // transform null object into an object
17831 if (is_null())
17832 {
17833 m_type = value_t::object;
17834 m_value = value_t::object;
17835 assert_invariant();
17836 }
17837
17838 // add element to array (perfect forwarding)
17839 auto res = m_value.object->emplace(std::forward<Args>(args)...);
17840 // create result iterator and set iterator to the result of emplace
17841 auto it = begin();
17842 it.m_it.object_iterator = res.first;
17843
17844 // return pair of iterator and boolean
17845 return {it, res.second};
17846 }
17847
17851 template<typename... Args>
17852 iterator insert_iterator(const_iterator pos, Args&& ... args)
17853 {
17854 iterator result(this);
17855 assert(m_value.array != nullptr);
17856
17857 auto insert_pos = std::distance(m_value.array->begin(), pos.m_it.array_iterator);
17858 m_value.array->insert(pos.m_it.array_iterator, std::forward<Args>(args)...);
17859 result.m_it.array_iterator = m_value.array->begin() + insert_pos;
17860
17861 // This could have been written as:
17862 // result.m_it.array_iterator = m_value.array->insert(pos.m_it.array_iterator, cnt, val);
17863 // but the return value of insert is missing in GCC 4.8, so it is written this way instead.
17864
17865 return result;
17866 }
17867
17890 iterator insert(const_iterator pos, const basic_json& val)
17891 {
17892 // insert only works for arrays
17893 if (JSON_LIKELY(is_array()))
17894 {
17895 // check if iterator pos fits to this JSON value
17896 if (JSON_UNLIKELY(pos.m_object != this))
17897 {
17898 JSON_THROW(invalid_iterator::create(202, "iterator does not fit current value"));
17899 }
17900
17901 // insert to array and return iterator
17902 return insert_iterator(pos, val);
17903 }
17904
17905 JSON_THROW(type_error::create(309, "cannot use insert() with " + std::string(type_name())));
17906 }
17907
17912 iterator insert(const_iterator pos, basic_json&& val)
17913 {
17914 return insert(pos, val);
17915 }
17916
17941 iterator insert(const_iterator pos, size_type cnt, const basic_json& val)
17942 {
17943 // insert only works for arrays
17944 if (JSON_LIKELY(is_array()))
17945 {
17946 // check if iterator pos fits to this JSON value
17947 if (JSON_UNLIKELY(pos.m_object != this))
17948 {
17949 JSON_THROW(invalid_iterator::create(202, "iterator does not fit current value"));
17950 }
17951
17952 // insert to array and return iterator
17953 return insert_iterator(pos, cnt, val);
17954 }
17955
17956 JSON_THROW(type_error::create(309, "cannot use insert() with " + std::string(type_name())));
17957 }
17958
17989 iterator insert(const_iterator pos, const_iterator first, const_iterator last)
17990 {
17991 // insert only works for arrays
17992 if (JSON_UNLIKELY(not is_array()))
17993 {
17994 JSON_THROW(type_error::create(309, "cannot use insert() with " + std::string(type_name())));
17995 }
17996
17997 // check if iterator pos fits to this JSON value
17998 if (JSON_UNLIKELY(pos.m_object != this))
17999 {
18000 JSON_THROW(invalid_iterator::create(202, "iterator does not fit current value"));
18001 }
18002
18003 // check if range iterators belong to the same JSON object
18004 if (JSON_UNLIKELY(first.m_object != last.m_object))
18005 {
18006 JSON_THROW(invalid_iterator::create(210, "iterators do not fit"));
18007 }
18008
18009 if (JSON_UNLIKELY(first.m_object == this))
18010 {
18011 JSON_THROW(invalid_iterator::create(211, "passed iterators may not belong to container"));
18012 }
18013
18014 // insert to array and return iterator
18015 return insert_iterator(pos, first.m_it.array_iterator, last.m_it.array_iterator);
18016 }
18017
18042 iterator insert(const_iterator pos, initializer_list_t ilist)
18043 {
18044 // insert only works for arrays
18045 if (JSON_UNLIKELY(not is_array()))
18046 {
18047 JSON_THROW(type_error::create(309, "cannot use insert() with " + std::string(type_name())));
18048 }
18049
18050 // check if iterator pos fits to this JSON value
18051 if (JSON_UNLIKELY(pos.m_object != this))
18052 {
18053 JSON_THROW(invalid_iterator::create(202, "iterator does not fit current value"));
18054 }
18055
18056 // insert to array and return iterator
18057 return insert_iterator(pos, ilist.begin(), ilist.end());
18058 }
18059
18083 void insert(const_iterator first, const_iterator last)
18084 {
18085 // insert only works for objects
18086 if (JSON_UNLIKELY(not is_object()))
18087 {
18088 JSON_THROW(type_error::create(309, "cannot use insert() with " + std::string(type_name())));
18089 }
18090
18091 // check if range iterators belong to the same JSON object
18092 if (JSON_UNLIKELY(first.m_object != last.m_object))
18093 {
18094 JSON_THROW(invalid_iterator::create(210, "iterators do not fit"));
18095 }
18096
18097 // passed iterators must belong to objects
18098 if (JSON_UNLIKELY(not first.m_object->is_object()))
18099 {
18100 JSON_THROW(invalid_iterator::create(202, "iterators first and last must point to objects"));
18101 }
18102
18103 m_value.object->insert(first.m_it.object_iterator, last.m_it.object_iterator);
18104 }
18105
18125 void update(const_reference j)
18126 {
18127 // implicitly convert null value to an empty object
18128 if (is_null())
18129 {
18130 m_type = value_t::object;
18131 m_value.object = create<object_t>();
18132 assert_invariant();
18133 }
18134
18135 if (JSON_UNLIKELY(not is_object()))
18136 {
18137 JSON_THROW(type_error::create(312, "cannot use update() with " + std::string(type_name())));
18138 }
18139 if (JSON_UNLIKELY(not j.is_object()))
18140 {
18141 JSON_THROW(type_error::create(312, "cannot use update() with " + std::string(j.type_name())));
18142 }
18143
18144 for (auto it = j.cbegin(); it != j.cend(); ++it)
18145 {
18146 m_value.object->operator[](it.key()) = it.value();
18147 }
18148 }
18149
18176 void update(const_iterator first, const_iterator last)
18177 {
18178 // implicitly convert null value to an empty object
18179 if (is_null())
18180 {
18181 m_type = value_t::object;
18182 m_value.object = create<object_t>();
18183 assert_invariant();
18184 }
18185
18186 if (JSON_UNLIKELY(not is_object()))
18187 {
18188 JSON_THROW(type_error::create(312, "cannot use update() with " + std::string(type_name())));
18189 }
18190
18191 // check if range iterators belong to the same JSON object
18192 if (JSON_UNLIKELY(first.m_object != last.m_object))
18193 {
18194 JSON_THROW(invalid_iterator::create(210, "iterators do not fit"));
18195 }
18196
18197 // passed iterators must belong to objects
18198 if (JSON_UNLIKELY(not first.m_object->is_object()
18199 or not last.m_object->is_object()))
18200 {
18201 JSON_THROW(invalid_iterator::create(202, "iterators first and last must point to objects"));
18202 }
18203
18204 for (auto it = first; it != last; ++it)
18205 {
18206 m_value.object->operator[](it.key()) = it.value();
18207 }
18208 }

18342 // lexicographical comparison operators //
18344
18347
18387 friend bool operator==(const_reference lhs, const_reference rhs) noexcept
18388 {
18389 const auto lhs_type = lhs.type();
18390 const auto rhs_type = rhs.type();
18391
18392 if (lhs_type == rhs_type)
18393 {
18394 switch (lhs_type)
18395 {
18396 case value_t::array:
18397 return *lhs.m_value.array == *rhs.m_value.array;
18398
18399 case value_t::object:
18400 return *lhs.m_value.object == *rhs.m_value.object;
18401
18402 case value_t::null:
18403 return true;
18404
18405 case value_t::string:
18406 return *lhs.m_value.string == *rhs.m_value.string;
18407
18408 case value_t::boolean:
18409 return lhs.m_value.boolean == rhs.m_value.boolean;
18410
18411 case value_t::number_integer:
18412 return lhs.m_value.number_integer == rhs.m_value.number_integer;
18413
18414 case value_t::number_unsigned:
18415 return lhs.m_value.number_unsigned == rhs.m_value.number_unsigned;
18416
18417 case value_t::number_float:
18418 return lhs.m_value.number_float == rhs.m_value.number_float;
18419
18420 default:
18421 return false;
18422 }
18423 }
18424 else if (lhs_type == value_t::number_integer and rhs_type == value_t::number_float)
18425 {
18426 return static_cast<number_float_t>(lhs.m_value.number_integer) == rhs.m_value.number_float;
18427 }
18428 else if (lhs_type == value_t::number_float and rhs_type == value_t::number_integer)
18429 {
18430 return lhs.m_value.number_float == static_cast<number_float_t>(rhs.m_value.number_integer);
18431 }
18432 else if (lhs_type == value_t::number_unsigned and rhs_type == value_t::number_float)
18433 {
18434 return static_cast<number_float_t>(lhs.m_value.number_unsigned) == rhs.m_value.number_float;
18435 }
18436 else if (lhs_type == value_t::number_float and rhs_type == value_t::number_unsigned)
18437 {
18438 return lhs.m_value.number_float == static_cast<number_float_t>(rhs.m_value.number_unsigned);
18439 }
18440 else if (lhs_type == value_t::number_unsigned and rhs_type == value_t::number_integer)
18441 {
18442 return static_cast<number_integer_t>(lhs.m_value.number_unsigned) == rhs.m_value.number_integer;
18443 }
18444 else if (lhs_type == value_t::number_integer and rhs_type == value_t::number_unsigned)
18445 {
18446 return lhs.m_value.number_integer == static_cast<number_integer_t>(rhs.m_value.number_unsigned);
18447 }
18448
18449 return false;
18450 }

18518
18545 friend bool operator<(const_reference lhs, const_reference rhs) noexcept
18546 {
18547 const auto lhs_type = lhs.type();
18548 const auto rhs_type = rhs.type();
18549
18550 if (lhs_type == rhs_type)
18551 {
18552 switch (lhs_type)
18553 {
18554 case value_t::array:
18555 // note parentheses are necessary, see
18556 // https://github.com/nlohmann/json/issues/1530
18557 return (*lhs.m_value.array) < (*rhs.m_value.array);
18558
18559 case value_t::object:
18560 return *lhs.m_value.object < *rhs.m_value.object;
18561
18562 case value_t::null:
18563 return false;
18564
18565 case value_t::string:
18566 return *lhs.m_value.string < *rhs.m_value.string;
18567
18568 case value_t::boolean:
18569 return lhs.m_value.boolean < rhs.m_value.boolean;
18570
18571 case value_t::number_integer:
18572 return lhs.m_value.number_integer < rhs.m_value.number_integer;
18573
18574 case value_t::number_unsigned:
18575 return lhs.m_value.number_unsigned < rhs.m_value.number_unsigned;
18576
18577 case value_t::number_float:
18578 return lhs.m_value.number_float < rhs.m_value.number_float;
18579
18580 default:
18581 return false;
18582 }
18583 }
18584 else if (lhs_type == value_t::number_integer and rhs_type == value_t::number_float)
18585 {
18586 return static_cast<number_float_t>(lhs.m_value.number_integer) < rhs.m_value.number_float;
18587 }
18588 else if (lhs_type == value_t::number_float and rhs_type == value_t::number_integer)
18589 {
18590 return lhs.m_value.number_float < static_cast<number_float_t>(rhs.m_value.number_integer);
18591 }
18592 else if (lhs_type == value_t::number_unsigned and rhs_type == value_t::number_float)
18593 {
18594 return static_cast<number_float_t>(lhs.m_value.number_unsigned) < rhs.m_value.number_float;
18595 }
18596 else if (lhs_type == value_t::number_float and rhs_type == value_t::number_unsigned)
18597 {
18598 return lhs.m_value.number_float < static_cast<number_float_t>(rhs.m_value.number_unsigned);
18599 }
18600 else if (lhs_type == value_t::number_integer and rhs_type == value_t::number_unsigned)
18601 {
18602 return lhs.m_value.number_integer < static_cast<number_integer_t>(rhs.m_value.number_unsigned);
18603 }
18604 else if (lhs_type == value_t::number_unsigned and rhs_type == value_t::number_integer)
18605 {
18606 return static_cast<number_integer_t>(lhs.m_value.number_unsigned) < rhs.m_value.number_integer;
18607 }
18608
18609 // We only reach this line if we cannot compare values. In that case,
18610 // we compare types. Note we have to call the operator explicitly,
18611 // because MSVC has problems otherwise.
18612 return operator<(lhs_type, rhs_type);
18613 }
18614

18620 std::is_scalar<ScalarType>::value, int>::type = 0>
18621 friend bool operator<(const_reference lhs, const ScalarType rhs) noexcept
18622 {
18623 return lhs < basic_json(rhs);
18624 }

18815 friend std::ostream& operator<<(std::ostream& o, const basic_json& j)
18816 {
18817 // read width member and use it as indentation parameter if nonzero
18818 const bool pretty_print = o.width() > 0;
18819 const auto indentation = pretty_print ? o.width() : 0;
18820
18821 // reset width to 0 for subsequent calls to this stream
18822 o.width(0);
18823
18824 // do the actual serialization
18825 serializer s(detail::output_adapter<char>(o), o.fill());
18826 s.dump(j, pretty_print, false, static_cast<unsigned int>(indentation));
18827 return o;
18828 }

18987 input_format_t format = input_format_t::json,
18988 const bool strict = true)
18989 {

19157 const char* type_name() const noexcept
19158 {
19159 {
19160 switch (m_type)
19161 {
19162 case value_t::null:

19164 case value_t::object:
19165 return "object";
19166 case value_t::array:

19168 case value_t::string:
19169 return "string";
19170 case value_t::boolean:
19171 return "boolean";
19172 case value_t::discarded:
19173 return "discarded";
19174 default:

19176 }
19177 }

20225
20227 // JSON Patch functions //
20229
20232
20280 basic_json patch(const basic_json& json_patch) const
20281 {
20282 // make a working copy to apply the patch to
20283 basic_json result = *this;
20284
20285 // the valid JSON Patch operations
20286 enum class patch_operations {add, remove, replace, move, copy, test, invalid};
20287
20288 const auto get_op = [](const std::string & op)
20289 {
20290 if (op == "add")
20291 {
20292 return patch_operations::add;
20293 }
20294 if (op == "remove")
20295 {
20296 return patch_operations::remove;
20297 }
20298 if (op == "replace")
20299 {
20300 return patch_operations::replace;
20301 }
20302 if (op == "move")
20303 {
20304 return patch_operations::move;
20305 }
20306 if (op == "copy")
20307 {
20308 return patch_operations::copy;
20309 }
20310 if (op == "test")
20311 {
20312 return patch_operations::test;
20313 }
20314
20315 return patch_operations::invalid;
20316 };
20317
20318 // wrapper for "add" operation; add value at ptr
20319 const auto operation_add = [&result](json_pointer & ptr, basic_json val)
20320 {
20321 // adding to the root of the target document means replacing it
20322 if (ptr.empty())
20323 {
20324 result = val;
20325 return;
20326 }
20327
20328 // make sure the top element of the pointer exists
20329 json_pointer top_pointer = ptr.top();
20330 if (top_pointer != ptr)
20331 {
20332 result.at(top_pointer);
20333 }
20334
20335 // get reference to parent of JSON pointer ptr
20336 const auto last_path = ptr.back();
20337 ptr.pop_back();
20338 basic_json& parent = result[ptr];
20339
20340 switch (parent.m_type)
20341 {
20342 case value_t::null:
20343 case value_t::object:
20344 {
20345 // use operator[] to add value
20346 parent[last_path] = val;
20347 break;
20348 }
20349
20350 case value_t::array:
20351 {
20352 if (last_path == "-")
20353 {
20354 // special case: append to back
20355 parent.push_back(val);
20356 }
20357 else
20358 {
20359 const auto idx = json_pointer::array_index(last_path);
20360 if (JSON_UNLIKELY(static_cast<size_type>(idx) > parent.size()))
20361 {
20362 // avoid undefined behavior
20363 JSON_THROW(out_of_range::create(401, "array index " + std::to_string(idx) + " is out of range"));
20364 }
20365
20366 // default case: insert add offset
20367 parent.insert(parent.begin() + static_cast<difference_type>(idx), val);
20368 }
20369 break;
20370 }
20371
20372 // if there exists a parent it cannot be primitive
20373 default: // LCOV_EXCL_LINE
20374 assert(false); // LCOV_EXCL_LINE
20375 }
20376 };
20377
20378 // wrapper for "remove" operation; remove value at ptr
20379 const auto operation_remove = [&result](json_pointer & ptr)
20380 {
20381 // get reference to parent of JSON pointer ptr
20382 const auto last_path = ptr.back();
20383 ptr.pop_back();
20384 basic_json& parent = result.at(ptr);
20385
20386 // remove child
20387 if (parent.is_object())
20388 {
20389 // perform range check
20390 auto it = parent.find(last_path);
20391 if (JSON_LIKELY(it != parent.end()))
20392 {
20393 parent.erase(it);
20394 }
20395 else
20396 {
20397 JSON_THROW(out_of_range::create(403, "key '" + last_path + "' not found"));
20398 }
20399 }
20400 else if (parent.is_array())
20401 {
20402 // note erase performs range check
20403 parent.erase(static_cast<size_type>(json_pointer::array_index(last_path)));
20404 }
20405 };
20406
20407 // type check: top level value must be an array
20408 if (JSON_UNLIKELY(not json_patch.is_array()))
20409 {
20410 JSON_THROW(parse_error::create(104, 0, "JSON patch must be an array of objects"));
20411 }
20412
20413 // iterate and apply the operations
20414 for (const auto& val : json_patch)
20415 {
20416 // wrapper to get a value for an operation
20417 const auto get_value = [&val](const std::string & op,
20418 const std::string & member,
20419 bool string_type) -> basic_json &
20420 {
20421 // find value
20422 auto it = val.m_value.object->find(member);
20423
20424 // context-sensitive error message
20425 const auto error_msg = (op == "op") ? "operation" : "operation '" + op + "'";
20426
20427 // check if desired value is present
20428 if (JSON_UNLIKELY(it == val.m_value.object->end()))
20429 {
20430 JSON_THROW(parse_error::create(105, 0, error_msg + " must have member '" + member + "'"));
20431 }
20432
20433 // check if result is of type string
20434 if (JSON_UNLIKELY(string_type and not it->second.is_string()))
20435 {
20436 JSON_THROW(parse_error::create(105, 0, error_msg + " must have string member '" + member + "'"));
20437 }
20438
20439 // no error: return value
20440 return it->second;
20441 };
20442
20443 // type check: every element of the array must be an object
20444 if (JSON_UNLIKELY(not val.is_object()))
20445 {
20446 JSON_THROW(parse_error::create(104, 0, "JSON patch must be an array of objects"));
20447 }
20448
20449 // collect mandatory members
20450 const std::string op = get_value("op", "op", true);
20451 const std::string path = get_value(op, "path", true);
20452 json_pointer ptr(path);
20453
20454 switch (get_op(op))
20455 {
20456 case patch_operations::add:
20457 {
20458 operation_add(ptr, get_value("add", "value", false));
20459 break;
20460 }
20461
20462 case patch_operations::remove:
20463 {
20464 operation_remove(ptr);
20465 break;
20466 }
20467
20468 case patch_operations::replace:
20469 {
20470 // the "path" location must exist - use at()
20471 result.at(ptr) = get_value("replace", "value", false);
20472 break;
20473 }
20474
20475 case patch_operations::move:
20476 {
20477 const std::string from_path = get_value("move", "from", true);
20478 json_pointer from_ptr(from_path);
20479
20480 // the "from" location must exist - use at()
20481 basic_json v = result.at(from_ptr);
20482
20483 // The move operation is functionally identical to a
20484 // "remove" operation on the "from" location, followed
20485 // immediately by an "add" operation at the target
20486 // location with the value that was just removed.
20487 operation_remove(from_ptr);
20488 operation_add(ptr, v);
20489 break;
20490 }
20491
20492 case patch_operations::copy:
20493 {
20494 const std::string from_path = get_value("copy", "from", true);
20495 const json_pointer from_ptr(from_path);
20496
20497 // the "from" location must exist - use at()
20498 basic_json v = result.at(from_ptr);
20499
20500 // The copy is functionally identical to an "add"
20501 // operation at the target location using the value
20502 // specified in the "from" member.
20503 operation_add(ptr, v);
20504 break;
20505 }
20506
20507 case patch_operations::test:
20508 {
20509 bool success = false;
20510 JSON_TRY
20511 {
20512 // check if "value" matches the one at "path"
20513 // the "path" location must exist - use at()
20514 success = (result.at(ptr) == get_value("test", "value", false));
20515 }
20516 JSON_INTERNAL_CATCH (out_of_range&)
20517 {
20518 // ignore out of range errors: success remains false
20519 }
20520
20521 // throw an exception if test fails
20522 if (JSON_UNLIKELY(not success))
20523 {
20524 JSON_THROW(other_error::create(501, "unsuccessful: " + val.dump()));
20525 }
20526
20527 break;
20528 }
20529
20530 default:
20531 {
20532 // op must be "add", "remove", "replace", "move", "copy", or
20533 // "test"
20534 JSON_THROW(parse_error::create(105, 0, "operation value '" + op + "' is invalid"));
20535 }
20536 }
20537 }
20538
20539 return result;
20540 }
20541
20575 JSON_NODISCARD
20576 static basic_json diff(const basic_json& source, const basic_json& target,
20577 const std::string& path = "")
20578 {
20579 // the patch
20580 basic_json result(value_t::array);
20581
20582 // if the values are the same, return empty patch
20583 if (source == target)
20584 {
20585 return result;
20586 }
20587
20588 if (source.type() != target.type())
20589 {
20590 // different types: replace value
20591 result.push_back(
20592 {
20593 {"op", "replace"}, {"path", path}, {"value", target}
20594 });
20595 return result;
20596 }
20597
20598 switch (source.type())
20599 {
20600 case value_t::array:
20601 {
20602 // first pass: traverse common elements
20603 std::size_t i = 0;
20604 while (i < source.size() and i < target.size())
20605 {
20606 // recursive call to compare array values at index i
20607 auto temp_diff = diff(source[i], target[i], path + "/" + std::to_string(i));
20608 result.insert(result.end(), temp_diff.begin(), temp_diff.end());
20609 ++i;
20610 }
20611
20612 // i now reached the end of at least one array
20613 // in a second pass, traverse the remaining elements
20614
20615 // remove my remaining elements
20616 const auto end_index = static_cast<difference_type>(result.size());
20617 while (i < source.size())
20618 {
20619 // add operations in reverse order to avoid invalid
20620 // indices
20621 result.insert(result.begin() + end_index, object(
20622 {
20623 {"op", "remove"},
20624 {"path", path + "/" + std::to_string(i)}
20625 }));
20626 ++i;
20627 }
20628
20629 // add other remaining elements
20630 while (i < target.size())
20631 {
20632 result.push_back(
20633 {
20634 {"op", "add"},
20635 {"path", path + "/" + std::to_string(i)},
20636 {"value", target[i]}
20637 });
20638 ++i;
20639 }
20640
20641 break;
20642 }
20643
20644 case value_t::object:
20645 {
20646 // first pass: traverse this object's elements
20647 for (auto it = source.cbegin(); it != source.cend(); ++it)
20648 {
20649 // escape the key name to be used in a JSON patch
20650 const auto key = json_pointer::escape(it.key());
20651
20652 if (target.find(it.key()) != target.end())
20653 {
20654 // recursive call to compare object values at key it
20655 auto temp_diff = diff(it.value(), target[it.key()], path + "/" + key);
20656 result.insert(result.end(), temp_diff.begin(), temp_diff.end());
20657 }
20658 else
20659 {
20660 // found a key that is not in o -> remove it
20661 result.push_back(object(
20662 {
20663 {"op", "remove"}, {"path", path + "/" + key}
20664 }));
20665 }
20666 }
20667
20668 // second pass: traverse other object's elements
20669 for (auto it = target.cbegin(); it != target.cend(); ++it)
20670 {
20671 if (source.find(it.key()) == source.end())
20672 {
20673 // found a key that is not in this -> add it
20674 const auto key = json_pointer::escape(it.key());
20675 result.push_back(
20676 {
20677 {"op", "add"}, {"path", path + "/" + key},
20678 {"value", it.value()}
20679 });
20680 }
20681 }
20682
20683 break;
20684 }
20685
20686 default:
20687 {
20688 // both primitive type: replace value
20689 result.push_back(
20690 {
20691 {"op", "replace"}, {"path", path}, {"value", target}
20692 });
20693 break;
20694 }
20695 }
20696
20697 return result;
20698 }
20699
20701
20703 // JSON Merge Patch functions //
20705
20708
20751 void merge_patch(const basic_json& apply_patch)
20752 {
20753 if (apply_patch.is_object())
20754 {
20755 if (not is_object())
20756 {
20757 *this = object();
20758 }
20759 for (auto it = apply_patch.begin(); it != apply_patch.end(); ++it)
20760 {
20761 if (it.value().is_null())
20762 {
20763 erase(it.key());
20764 }
20765 else
20766 {
20767 operator[](it.key()).merge_patch(it.value());
20768 }
20769 }
20770 }
20771 else
20772 {
20773 *this = apply_patch;
20774 }
20775 }
20776
20778 };
